\section{Overview}\label{sec:overview}

The key idea is to \emph{desugar} the source verse
programs into a core language that is \vcshort (the ICFP23 calculus)
extended with
%
(1) \emph{syntax} to record \emph{assumptions} and \emph{obligations},
%
(2) \emph{rewrite rules} that use the assumptions to discharge obligations.

The verifier takes as input a surface term $t$ and desugars it into a
verifier term $e$. Next, the verifier repeatedly applies \emph{all}
the rewrite rules, that is, the ICFP23 rules \emph{and}
the new verification rules, such that either
%
(a)~we obtain a term |e'| such that $\isdone{e'}$, \ie which
contains no obligations, in a covariant position, in which case
|t| is \emph{accepted}, or
%
(b)~we obtain a normal form |e'| that still contains obligations
in a covariant position, in which case |t| is \emph{rejected}, or
%
(c)~the rewriting times out, in which case |t| is \emph{rejected}.

Next, we describe the extensions to the syntax \cref{sec:syntax},
explain the desugaring by means of examples \cref{sec:desugaring},
present the verification rewrite rules \cref{sec:verification}, and
finally show a few examples that show how the verifier works from
end-to-end.

